+    deployment, Instance selection is implicit (see [ARCH]
+    Section 4.2.2.4) and the notions of Control Header, SCHC Instance,
+    and Discriminator MAY be omitted.

- A full SCHC implementation with the right configuration MUST
- interoperate with a specific SCHClet.  The SCHClet in question may
- not necessarily handle these configurations itself (e.g. it may be a
- fixed implementation with no parametrization possible on its side),
- they can be reinterpreted as a full SCHC implementation would.  For
- example, an implementer of a compression SCHClet may never formally
- use Rule Management, Discriminators, SCHC Header or other notions
- defined in the SCHC Architecture, these can be inferred by the
- knowledgeable SCHC practitioner.  It is of course RECOMMENDED that a
- SCHClet provides a complete picture of its use in the context of a
- full SCHC implementation.
+ A full SCHC implementation with the right configuration MUST
+ interoperate with a specific SCHClet.  The SCHClet in question may
+ not necessarily handle these configurations itself (e.g. it may be a
+ fixed implementation with no parametrization possible on its side);
+ interoperability holds because the SCHClet's Context and Set of Rules
+ are compatible with those of the peer (see [ARCH] Section 6.2), and
+ the elided notions can be reconstructed as a full SCHC implementation
+ would.  For example, an implementer of a compression SCHClet may never
+ formally reify Rule management, Discriminators, the Control Header, or
+ other notions defined in the SCHC Architecture; these can be inferred
+ by the knowledgeable SCHC practitioner.  It is of course RECOMMENDED
+ that a SCHClet provides a complete picture of its use in the context of
+ a full SCHC implementation.


## Section 4 (Formal SCHClet definition and validation)

- A SCHClet is designed to be interoperable with both minimal and full
- SCHC implementations.  For instance, an endpoint may implement a
- single SCHClet for a specific function (e.g., IPsec compression)
- while the corresponding peer uses a comprehensive SCHC implementation
- that supports multiple SCHClets.  Proper configuration and
- negotiation mechanisms are essential to ensure that both ends
- correctly interpret the SCHC context.
+ A SCHClet is designed to be interoperable with both minimal and full
+ SCHC implementations.  For instance, an Endpoint may host a single
+ Instance implementing a single SCHClet for a specific function (e.g.,
+ IPsec compression) while the corresponding peer uses a comprehensive
+ SCHC implementation that supports multiple SCHClets.  Because SCHC
+ assumes that the Context is static and provisioned before use (see
+ [ARCH] Section 1), a consistent, pre-provisioned Context on both ends
+ is essential to ensure that they correctly interpret the SCHC Context.


## Section 4.1 (SCHC Stratum Header, SCHC Instance, Discriminator)

- 4.1.  SCHC Stratum Header, SCHC Instance, Discriminator
+ 4.1.  Control Header, SCHC Instance, Discriminator

- A SCHClet operates on a single Stratum and on a single SCHC Instance.
- As such, there is no need to specify SCHC Stratum Header, which is
- always fully elided.  In addition, there is no need for a
- Discriminator.  Documents specifying the use of a SCHClet MAY omit
- the specification of SCHC Stratum Header, SCHC Instance and/or
- Discriminator considerations.
+ A SCHClet is hosted within a single SCHC Instance and operates on a
+ single Stratum.  As such, there is no need to specify a Control Header,
+ which is always absent (fully elided).  In addition, Instance selection
+ is implicit and there is no need for a Discriminator.  Documents
+ specifying the use of a SCHClet MAY omit the specification of Control
+ Header, SCHC Instance and/or Discriminator considerations.

- It is RECOMMENDED if there are more than one SCHC Instances to use a
- Full SCHC Implementation within the Full SCHC Architecture.  While
- not recommended, a SCHC Stratum Instance MAY be defined as a SCHClet,
- and combined with other SCHClets to achieve the functionality of a
- complete SCHC Stratum implementation.
+ It is RECOMMENDED that deployments requiring more than one SCHC
+ Instance use a full SCHC implementation as described in [ARCH].  While
+ not recommended, a single-Instance function MAY be defined as a
+ SCHClet, and combined with other SCHClets within an Instance to
+ achieve the functionality of a complete SCHC Instance.


## Section 5.1 (IPsec Compression SCHClet)

- *  Functionality: This SCHClet implements only the compression rules
-    defined in RFC8724 and a limited set of Context-Dependent
-    Attributes (CoDAs).
+ *  Functionality: This SCHClet implements only the compression Rules
+    defined in RFC8724 and a limited set of Compression/Decompression
+    Actions (CDAs).

- *  Deployment: The implementation is tailored for IPsec environments,
-    focusing solely on compression without engaging in rule management
-    or SCHC Stratum functions.
+ *  Deployment: The implementation is tailored for IPsec environments,
+    focusing solely on compression without engaging in Rule management
+    or Control Header functions.

- *  Interoperability: Although minimal, this SCHClet must be
-    configured to operate alongside endpoints that might use full SCHC
-    implementations.
+ *  Interoperability: Although minimal, this SCHClet must be
+    configured with a Context compatible with the Endpoints that might
+    use full SCHC implementations (see [ARCH] Section 6.2).


